  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, USA)\n- First international recognition of money laundering as a criminal activity\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- FATF establishment (1989)\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n\n3. Regulatory Developments\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Mandatory reporting of suspicious transactions\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Increased international cooperation\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Regulations covering cryptocurrency transactions\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Machine learning and AI-based detection systems\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Increased focus on beneficial ownership transparency\n- Broader scope of anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Stricter penalties for non-compliance\n- Greater emphasis on preventing terrorist financing\n\n6. Global Collaboration\n- Standardized international AML frameworks\n- Information sharing between financial institutions\n- Cross-border enforcement mechanisms\n\nThe legislation continues to evolve, becoming more comprehensive and technologically sophisticated to address emerging financial crime challenges.",
